<BaseLayout title="About — Biochemistry-pedia" description="What Biochemistry-pedia is, and the rules that keep it honest.">
  <article class="wrap prose-col" style="padding-top: var(--ddp-space-12)">
    <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1>An interactive textbook that refuses to make things up.</h1>

    <p>
      Biochemistry-pedia is an interactive site for learning biochemistry, built for the
      ~750 students who take BIOL&nbsp;3030 at the University of Virginia each year.
      It is the deliverable for a small AI&nbsp;Catalyst grant. The content comes
      from material Prof.&nbsp;Deppmann already has: twenty years of lectures and the
      book <em>The Molecule Hunters</em>.
    </p>

    <h2>The rules that keep it honest</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>No invented molecules.</strong> Every 3D structure is loaded live by accession ID from RCSB&nbsp;PDB (macromolecules) or PubChem (small molecules). Nothing is drawn by an AI, ever.</li>
      <li><strong>No unverified AI images.</strong> An AI-generated figure is allowed only if it is flagged and a named human has fact-checked it. An unreviewed one fails the build — the site literally won't compile.</li>
      <li><strong>No borrowed questions.</strong> Every practice and MCAT-style question is written for this site, with a verified answer and an explanation. MCAT-style items are original, not real AAMC questions.</li>
      <li><strong>Honest media.</strong> Videos and podcasts are embedded from their source, never rehosted.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What's not here yet</h2>
    <p>
      The AI tutor and the "talk to a scientist" characters are intentionally not
      built yet. A tutor that is confidently wrong would do real harm, so that
      part waits until it can be grounded in the course material and clearly
      labelled. This first version is about getting one lesson <em>right</em>.
    </p>

    <p class="src-meta">
      Code is MIT-licensed and open. Lesson narrative and scientist profiles are
      the authors' intellectual property (see the repository's NOTICE).
    </p>

    <p><a href="/">← Back to lessons</a></p>
  </article>

